A persistent challenge in cardiac image segmentation is the model’s ability to adapt to features across scale variations. Inspired by the observation that varying kernel sizes in convolutions can yield diverse receptive fields [16], which enables effective local feature perception, we propose MSVSS blocks. These blocks leverage the global modeling capabilities of VSS [9] while enhancing the perception of scale variations through multi-scale depth-wise convolutions, ensuring comprehensive pattern recognition in cardiac images. The MSVSS block consists of parallel multi-scale depth-wise convolutions, a channel integration branch, and a calibration branch. Specifically, the parallel depth-wise convolutions [17] with different kernel sizes are employed to extract multi-scale feature representations. Since depth-wise convolutions ignore the inter-channel relationships, we introduce the channel integration branch, which employs channel shuffle [18] to capture and integrate inter-channel dependencies. Meanwhile, the calibration branch is designed to refine overlooked features in the channel integration branch. To achieve both global understanding and local scale perception, these two branches multiplex the same VSS block, built upon feature maps with scale awareness, thereby enabling comprehensive visual understanding while reducing computation complexity. As illustrated in Fig. 1(a),  the multi-scale features are derived from the input feature map Xin ∈ RH×W ×C using the following equation:  Y=  X  ks∈KS  DWConvks(Xin) + Xin (1)  where DWConvks(·) denotes a depth-wise convolution with a kernel size of ks. KS denotes the set of convolution kernel sizes, given by {1 × 1, 3 × 3, 5 × 5}.